# Mycelium Architecture Rules

## Layer Boundaries

- UI → ViewModel → Repository → Relay/DB. Never reverse the dependency direction.
- Cybin library (`cybin/`) must not depend on Android Context, Compose, Room, or any app-layer code.
- ViewModels never import from `ui/` packages. Repositories never import from `viewmodel/`.

## Module Boundary

- `cybin/` = Nostr protocol: events, filters, crypto, NIPs, relay transport (Ktor WebSocket)
- `app/` = Android application: UI, ViewModels, repositories, services, Room database
- Changes are picked up immediately via Gradle composite build — no publish step needed

## State Management

- Use `StateFlow` / `SharedFlow` for reactive state in repositories and ViewModels
- Use `MutableState` / `remember` only inside `@Composable` functions
- Activity-scoped VMs: `AppViewModel`, `AccountStateViewModel`, `FeedStateViewModel`
- Screen-scoped VMs: everything else in `viewmodel/`

## Critical File Awareness

Files over 1,000 lines require extra care. Always read before editing:
- `MyceliumNavigation.kt` (~5,230 lines) — all routes
- `NoteCard.kt` (~3,800 lines) — universal note display
- `NotesRepository.kt` (~2,900 lines) — feed pipeline
- `AccountStateViewModel.kt` (~2,400 lines) — account state
- `CybinRelayPool.kt` (~1,230 lines) — relay transport

## Relay Sovereignty

- Never hardcode relay URLs
- Never override user relay preferences
- Relay failures are expected — degrade gracefully
- Use `RelayHealthTracker` scoring for relay selection
